Overload.descr:
Counts all objects matching a given search criteria that are contained in the supplied object.
			Use PARTY (-357) to search the whole party.
			UI_count_objects("PARTY, SHAPE_GEM, QUALITY_ANY, FRAME_ANY");

Gets the direction the first object should face to see the second object.
			Best used as a variable to enable the act of turning towards the second object.
			UI_direction_from(LORTHONDO, AVATAR);

Displays the selected gump on screen and prints lines of runic text on-screen.
			What font is used to draw the text depends on the gump shown, and is currently hard-coded (as of 2009/02/26).
			UI_display_runes(44, ["REPORT", "THIS", "SIGN"]);

Causes the screen to fade to or from black.
				The fade type, if true, fades from black; if false, fades to black.
				UI_fade_palette(12, 1, FADE_FROM_BLACK);

Gets the name of one or more objects.
			Despite the name, this intrinsic can be called for any object, not just NPCs;
			for non-NPCs, the return is the text displayed when you click the object.

Gives the last item in the 'last created' stack to the specified container or NPC.
			This intrinsic ignores volume, and is quite likely to succeed; 
			the given object is popped from the 'last created' stack only if the intrinsic succeeds.

Checks if a key is in the keyring.
			Note that the keyring is a global object;
			multiple keyrings will share the same list of keys.

Determines if a mouse exists.
			Exult always returns true;
			the original games will return true if a mouse if present, false otherwise.

Moves the specified object to a new location in the game world.
			This move is instantaneous, and is often used for teleportation in the original usecode.
			UI_move_object(PARTY, [1500, 2950, 0], false);

Creates a sprite effect from 'SPRITES.VGA'.
			This sprite effect is tied to 'obj'; if 'obj' moves, the sprite will move along.
			UI_obj_sprite_effect(THOXA, SPRITE_WHITE_LIGHTNING, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, -1);

Stores the current conversation options and clears all choices.
			The dialog options are stored in a LIFO stack that persists until the dialog ends;
			before that point, the stored options can be retrieved with a call to UI_pop_answers intrinsic.

Removes the count of the shape, quality and frame that are contained by the object.
			'unknown' is an unknown flag which is ignored by Exult;
			I think it is safe to omit it from the parameter list, but I am not sure.

Stops the music and restarts the game from the last save.
			The original games started from the beginning of the game;
			Exult does it differently to preserve the last quicksave.

Sets the position of the planets in the orrery at Moonglow.
			The intrinsic tries to find 'Planet Britania' near the specified location;
			it will delete the nearby planets, if any, and create new ones in the required positions.
